{"id": 100527, "acmi_id": "181521", "title": "Bwana Devil", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "bwana-devil", "creator_credit": "Arch Oboler", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "United States, 1952", "thumbnail": {"image_url": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.1200x1200_q85.jpg", "has_video": false}, "record_type": "group", "type": "Film", "is_on_display": true, "last_on_display_place": "ACMI: Gallery 1", "last_on_display_date": "2031-02-16", "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "first_production_date": "1952-01-01T10:00:00+10:00", "brief_description": "<p>Filmmakers felt threatened by the arrival of TV in 1948 and sought ways to keep audiences coming to cinemas. One way was 3D movies, and Bwana Devil was the first 3D colour feature film.</p>", "constellations_primary": [{"id": 50, "name": "Supplementing cinema", "description": "A celebration of b-grade cinema's never-ending quest for more, more, more."}], "constellations_other": [], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Bwana Devil</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "<p>Arch Oboler</p>", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>United States, 1952</p>", "description": "<p>&#8220;A lion in your lap! A lover in your arms! Newer than television!”</p>\n<p>That’s what Arch Oboler’s <i>Bwana Devil</i> promised in 1952. TV had arrived in America four years earlier and filmmakers had started experimenting with ways to keep audiences in cinemas. One experiment was 3D movies, and <i>Bwana Devil</i> was the first 3D colour feature film. At the time, industry bible Variety hailed 3D as “the next big thing”, and <i>LIFE</i> magazine captured the premiere with a major spread and this iconic picture of the audience. The film was panned by critics but made $2.5 million US dollars, something TV definitely couldn’t do yet.</p>", "description_for_label": ["<p>&#8220;A lion in your lap! A lover in your arms! Newer than television!”</p>\n<p>That’s what Arch Oboler’s <i>Bwana Devil</i> promised in 1952. TV had arrived in America four years earlier and filmmakers had started experimenting with ways to keep audiences in cinemas. One experiment was 3D movies, and <i>Bwana Devil</i> was the first 3D colour feature film. At the time, industry bible Variety hailed 3D as “the next big thing”, and <i>LIFE</i> magazine captured the premiere with a major spread and this iconic picture of the audience. The film was panned by critics but made $2.5 million US dollars, something TV definitely couldn’t do yet.</p>"], "credit_line_for_label": "", "details": [{"label": "Curatorial section", "display_values": ["The Story of the Moving Image&nbsp;→ Moving Pictures&nbsp;→ 08. Immersive Innovations&nbsp;→ MI-08-C01"]}], "stats": {"tap_count": 2395}, "links": [{"url": "https://www.justwatch.com/us/movie/bwana-devil", "title": "Stream, rent or buy at <span>JustWatch</span>", "source": "justwatch"}], "creators_primary": [{"id": 1054034, "name": "Arch Oboler", "creator_id": 43624, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}], "creators_other": [], "video_links": [], "media_note": null, "images": [{"id": 13081, "image_file": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg", "image_file_thumbnail": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.1200x1200_q85.jpg", "image_file_xs": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.480x480_q85.jpg", "image_file_s": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.960x960_q85.jpg", "image_file_m": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.1920x1920_q85.jpg", "image_file_l": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/P180381_G091.jpg.3840x3840_q85.jpg", "caption": "", "credit_line": "", "alt_text": "", "width": 3431, "height": 5100, "access_level": "View anywhere"}, {"id": 13288, "image_file": "https://acmi-public-api.s3.amazonaws.com/image/AEO180820_BwanaDevil3Dglasses_Left.jpg", "image_file_thumbn